      <hedline>
        <hl1>Israeli Interests</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jerry Rapp letter replies to June 8 editorial criticizing Israel's Shas party for calling for new elections</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Political Turmoil in Israel'' (editorial, June 8):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Political Turmoil in Israel'' (editorial, June 8):</p>
        <p>You say Shas was wrong to call for new elections because it should ''subordinate its pursuit of parochial causes to the wider Israeli interest in negotiating peace.''</p>
        <p>Shas's main concern, and the reason it has 17 seats in Parliament, has consistently been to provide desperately needed social and educational services for its constituency, many of whom are on the lower economic rungs of Israeli society.</p>
        <p>The pursuit of parochial interests has long been a cornerstone and driving force within democratic societies like, for example, the United States. Why should Shas be different?</p>
        <p>JERRY RAPP  New York, June 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
